metadata.name: Daydream #44
metadata.description:
In the unfolding of this work created in p5.js, my intention was to sculpt images with the ability to open the doors of our minds to an enigmatic and hidden world. It was a conscious effort to create a palette of sensations that would transport us to places where mystery resides in shadows and curves.
Press "s" to save the image.

metadata.name: Pixel Spaceships #212
metadata.description:
"Pixel Spaceships" is retro pixel pop art.  Spaceship-like forms are algorithmically generated by the hundreds, even thousands!  It is an exploration of generative algorithms, an examination of limited perception and the power of suggestion, and intended to evoke a nostalgia for the artistic sensibilities imposed by the hardware limitations of early arcade machines.

Further write-up:  https://www.davebollinger.us/pixelspaceships

Presented in a form suitable for large-format print if desired.  Each minting provides up to 100 retries via parameters to help obtain a preferred style.  (Though note that some features are quite rare, so a bit of luck may still be involved.)  Exploration is encouraged!

CONTROLS:

Press 's' to save the image.

Press a number key to adjust internal resolution (do this prior to saving):
  '1' : 1200px x  1800px ( 4" x  6" @300dpi) (default)
  '2' : 2400px x  3600px ( 8" x 12" @300dpi)
  '3' : 3600px x  5400px (12" x 18" @300dpi)
  '4' : 4800px x  7200px (16" x 24" @300dpi)
  '5' : 6000px x  9000px (20" x 30" @300dpi)
  '6' : 7200px x 10800px (24" x 36" @300dpi)

Note that changing the resolution will force the image to regenerate.  Regeneration at higher resolutions may take longer, particularly for complex scenes and/or rare features.

metadata.name: Cellular Skyscrapers #173
metadata.description:
A "Cellular Skyscraper" originates from a 15x15 grid with 15x3 cells randomly assigned the 'alive' state. According to the cellular automaton rule chosen from the transaction hash 24 new generations are calculated and placed on top of each other.

There are four different rules available (listed in Golly notation) all based on the Moore neighbourhood: 

B3/S23 (Game of Life)
B36/S125 (2x2)
B368/S245 (Morley)
B3/S234 (didn't find a name for it but produces interesting large structures)

After all generations have been calculated the algorithm searches through the complete 3D grid to find the one structure consisting of the most connected alive cells - cells are connected when they have at least one alive neighbour in any of the three axis.

Features are cell count, height, highlight color, ca rule and antenna count.

Extra: press 'd' to download the structure as a .gltf file to import into Blender or other software.
 
Enjoy!

metadata.name: Dynamic generations #162
metadata.description:
A classic cellular automata updates its state with a static rule based on the state of its neighbor.

This collection was created with cellular automata with an extension of that idea. Here the state and the rule are updated based on the state of its neighbor, here the rule changes in every iteration, here the rule is dynamic.

That change moves cellular automata to another level of complexity.

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #651
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: Silk(Fx) #163
metadata.description:
Silk captures the elegance that mirrors the smoothness of flowing fabric. The layered textures evoke the softness of silk, while the shimmering hues radiate a delicate translucence. Utilizing alpha channels and blending modes, light and color merge seamlessly.

1% change to get a RGB iteration

Press "l" to view the light version
Press "e" in live mode for a PNG download
Press (1-5) to change resolution

Lammetje december 2024

metadata.name: Miniscapes #264
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)
